We could use this as our baseline home court, but I believe this
overstates the home court advantage. The reason is each team gets to
pick its non-conference schedule each year which can lead to unbalanced
results. Good programs will schedule weaker opponents at home to make
money and get wins. In the professional ranks where the schedule is
created to be balanced, just looking at home results would be closer to
accurate than in college. Sure enough, if we look at the win percentage
by month we see in November and December when non-conference games are
being played, the win percentage is much higher than in January or
February.



Conference Results
The next way to look at it is to analyze just conference games. The
benefit of this method is the conference set the schedule so it should
be more balanced. A lot of conferences also have teams playing at each
team’s home. Also, for the most part, the teams in the conference have
similar skill levels to where home court advantage matters more in who
wins.


