These numbers are lower than the all home games as expected. We also
see a slight downward trend with a big drop during the 2021 season.
Early on home teams win around 62% of games, it drops to around 60%, and
then 58% in the two most recent seasons.
Home and Away Results
The last way to analyze this is to look at teams that played home and
home games and see what the overall win percentage is. They are most
commonly conference games so I expect similar results as above.
Home Court Stability
It is important to determine how quickly home court advantage
stabilizes for each season. This is because if home court advantage
changes in the early (2021 due to reduced crowds) we need to pick up on
it quickly during the season to adjust our predictions and ratings
adjustments for that season. It is easy to know the home court advantage
when the season completes, but that does not provide any help for in
season projections.
Future Steps
The above two options is just a broad way to analyze home court. It
gets you most of the way there without taking further steps to get the
last 10% or so correct. The There are more ways to take home court
calculations to the next level. There are a few other factors that could
impact home court.
Distance traveled by the road team. The further traveled the more
jet lag and other impacts you could see. My assumption is east to west
travel is harder than north to south, but will need to confirm.
Days spent on the road. Most road trips consist of two games so
perhaps being on the second game and away from your bed longer could
have an impact.
Time of the game. A west coast team playing on the east coast in the
afternoon could be earlier than they are used to playing. Similarly an
east coast team playing on the west coast at night might be tired and
not at peak performance levels.
Arena specific impacts. A louder crowd might also have an impact.
Also if it is a large gym it can impact the visual oft he opposing team
and cause them to shoot worse.
